body:
@pchote : Thanks for the review. I'm glad that the overall approach is acceptable, so I'll tackle using only integer calculations again.

@reaperrr : I've rebased it. Until I've done the float -> integer rebase, you can at least go ahead and give it a playtest, to see if it could suit your overall requirements.
I've done tests in TS so far by making disruptors and ghost stalkers fire at a point on the other side of a concrete wall.
(Again, excuse the resulting in-game jumpiness of the 'projectile blocked' code. I still need to revisit that.)

@pchote: I've addressed the comments, except for the use of WPos.Lerp.
For the life of me I cannot get it to work correctly using that. Regardless of how I try to cast to `(int)` I keep getting the function then only ever 'intersecting' at either the beam head or the beam tail.

If this is a critical issue, then I'll try and address it again. But otherwise I'd rather leave it for the follow-up PR that will implement the HomingLineImpactProjectile. (I.e. the way the TS disruptors are supposed to track their target with their beam, even if the target moves.)

@matija-hustic I've added the `outOfWeaponRange` check so 'long duration' beams (such as TS disruptors) should now stop firing when you move the unit out of range while it is firing.

Regarding the other issue (zero length beams being fired) I had reproduced it, but since the changes for the `outOfWeaponRange` check I have not yet encountered it again (despite trying).
So I believe that has been fixed as well, but please also try and reproduce this again.

![temp](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2726355/10640542/6381691a-7815-11e5-9dae-20f62b44a5dc.png)
@reaperrr Cannot seem to reproduce. I had just run make -> all again.
Or is it that the beams above are too wide as they are now?
